04695nam a22006375i 9780228007494DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280074947 a10.1515/97802280074942doi  a(DE-B1597)655029  a(OCoLC)1223033843  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1055.B7bL58 2021 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a971.4/020922231 aLittle, J.I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReading the Diaries of Henry Trent :bThe Everyday Life of a Canadian Englishman, 1842-1898 /cJ.I. Little. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b15 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Rural, Wildland, and Resource Studies ;v1400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tBoyhood and Youth -- tEmerging Manhood, Part 1 -- tEmerging Manhood, Part 2 -- tManhood -- tOld Age -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe personal journals examined in Reading the Diaries of Henry Trent are not the witty, erudite, and gracefully written exercises that have drawn the attention of most biographers and literary scholars. Prosaic, ungrammatical, and poorly spelled, the fifteen surviving volumes of Henry Trent's hitherto unexamined diaries are nevertheless a treasure for the social and cultural historian.Henry Trent was born in England in 1826, the son of a British naval officer. When he was still a boy, his father decided to begin a new life as a landed gentleman and moved the family to Lower Canada. At the age of sixteen Trent began writing in a diary, which he maintained, intermittently, for more than fifty years. As a lonely youth he narrates days spent hunting and trapping in the woods owned by his father. On the threshold of manhood and in search of a vocation, he writes about his experiences in London and then on Vancouver Island during the gold rush. And finally, as the father of a large family, he describes the daily struggle to make ends meet on the farm he inherited in Quebec's lower St Francis valley.As it follows Trent through the different stages of his long life, Reading the Diaries of Henry Trent explores the complexities of class and colonialism, gender roles within the rural family, and the transition from youth to manhood to old age. The diaries provide a rare opportunity to read the thoughts and follow the experiences of a man who, like many Victorian-era immigrants of the privileged class, struggled to adapt to the Canadian environment during the rise of the industrial age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglishzQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aEnglishzQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aFarm lifezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aFarm lifezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aFarmerszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aFarmerszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aImmigrantszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aImmigrantszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aSocial classeszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial classeszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228007494?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228007494423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228007494/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-12746